@node SUPPORT "SNOOPY SUPPORT TOOLS"
The directory "support/" contains several tools you will find usefull in your work with Snoopy (given that you see any sense in doing so ;-). These tools are provided together with their sourcecodes under the terms of the Snoopy @{"distribution" Link DISTRIBUTION}. They are :

	* @{"BUILDWATCH" Link BUILDWATCH } - build watch commands for an FD file
	* @{"TASKLIST" Link TASKLIST } - show the names of all existing tasks
	
@endnode

@node BUILDWATCH "BUILDWATCH"
	In case you have trouble making @{"script files" Link SCRIPT } for your libraries, try this tool. It takes as input the base name for a FD file, that fits to the following name description :

		FD:<base>_lib.fd

	Example:

		buildwatch dos

	Builds all commands for the dos.library from the file FD:dos_lib.fd

	The results are given to stdout - so you must redirect this if you want to get a script file. You can then hand-edit the result to take only the functions you wish to include. Also note that a script generated by BUILDWATCH is not sensible to the actual data types - BUILDWATCH assumes all data to be LONG registers; so it doesn't recognize STRPTRs for example. Probably what you would do is :

	- Generate a scriptfile with BUILDWATCH
	- make your own copy of this scriptfile and handedit it to 
	  contain 
	  
	  a) only those few functions you are interested in 
	     (its not very reasonable to Snoop into all of Execs stuff at
	     the same time, for instance...) 
	  b) proper output formats (e.g. replace %lx with %s for strings
	     and so on)
@endnode

@node TASKLIST "TASKLIST"
	This is a very small tool that gives you a list of the names of all tasks currently active in your system. If you don't have any other monitor program at hand, you can use "tasklist" to see if you can put some @{"hide" Link HIDE } statements in your Snoopy monitor file. "tasklist" has no arguments or tricky features; just try it and look what happens ;-)
@endnode

@node HISTORY "HISTORY"
	This page describes the changes that came about the different release versions of Snoopy

1.0	First released version.
1.1	- added PRI keyword
1.2	- BASE keyword now can handle a specific library version 
	- SHOW keyword added
	- rewrote this document to fit what one might call
	  "the latest developments in the wide field of the English Language" ;-)
	- tested with ENFORCER and found no hits (lucky me!)
1.3     - internal bugfixes only
1.4     Major update 
	- enables register indirect "due to popular demand"
	- workbench interface
	- detaches itself automagically
	- added snoopy.doc
1.5	Bugfixes
	- fixed bug in 1.4 causing 68000 machines to crash ->see @{"EXPERT MODE" Link EXPERTMODE}
	- added STICKY option
	- added QUIET option
	- added special notes on ENFORCER and other MMU tools
	- no more Printfs() for errors, uses EasyReq() instead (because after
	  detaching the DOS window might be closed)
@endnode

@node EXPERTMODE "EXPERT MODE" 
	Starting with 1.4, Snoopy enables snooping of register indirect - for experts only. The problem is this: At the time Snoopy looks at your function registers, it does NOT know which registers are of interest, so it just looks at ALL registers. This causes no problem if you just look at the registers, but if you want to see register indirect, you have two problems :

	* Ax could be odd (e.g. "A0=$00000001")
	  This causes 68000 cpus to crash with $3 ("odd address register")

	* Ax could be zero or, more precisely, pointing to an invalid address
	  This causes MMU controllers such as "ENFORCER" to crash with $4
	  ("invalid address")
	
	This means, that if you own a 68000 cpu, you should NEVER try the EXPERT mode, you will MOST LIKELY crash sooner or later (probably sooner). If you own a 68020 or higher CPU (like my smart 040 ;-) you can use the expert mode and look at register indirect, but NEVER use it together with some memory watchdog like all those CBM debugging tools. YOU WILL GET LOADS OF ERRORS FROM ENFORCER if you are in EXPERT mode, but EXPERT mode is for EXPERTS so just don't care if you are a fucking rockstar (=looser). 
@endnode

